{"title_page": "Eddie Hall", "text_new": "{{short description|British strongman}}\n{{for|the racing driver|Eddie Hall (racing driver)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Eddie Hall\n| nickname = The Beast\n| residence = [[Clayton, Newcastle-under-Lyme]], England\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = 250px\n| birth_name = Edward Stephen Hall<ref>{{cite web|title=500kg / 1102lbs Deadlift UNSEEN FOOTAGE! 500k Subs Special|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mnZ4ftlifik&t=1094|accessdate=26 Feb 2020 |quote=Watch at 18:14}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|1|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], [[Staffordshire]], England\n| spouse = Alexandra Hall\n| occupation = Strongman, actor\n| sport = [[Strongman (strength athlete)|Strongman]]\n| height = 186 cm<ref name=bio/>\n| weight = 164 kg<ref name=bio/>\n| pb = {{ubl|'''Deadlift''': {{convert|500|kg|1}} (2016, '''WR''') |'''Axle press''': {{convert|216|kg|1}} (2017, '''WR''') }}\n| show-medals = yes\n| medaltemplates = {{CompetitionRecordCountry | {{GBR}} }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[World's Strongest Man]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordQualifier| [[2012 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordQualifier| [[2013 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSixth| [[2014 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFourth| [[2015 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordThird| [[2016 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst| [[2017 World's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Arnold Strongman Classic]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSixth | 2015 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordNinth | 2016 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Europe's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSecond | 2017| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Giants Live]]}}\n{{CompetitionRecordFourth | 2012 Australia| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSecond | 2013 Hungary |}}\n{{CompetitionRecordThird | 2014 Hungary |}}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Britain's Strongest Man]]}}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Britain's Strongest Man|2014 Britain's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Britain's Strongest Man|2015 Britain's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Britain's Strongest Man|2016 Britain's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Britain's Strongest Man|2017 Britain's Strongest Man]]|| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Britain's Strongest Man|2018 Britain's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[UK's Strongest Man]]}}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2011 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2012 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2013 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2014 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2015 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[UK's Strongest Man|2016 UK's Strongest Man]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[England's Strongest Man]]}}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[England's Strongest Man|2010 England's Strongest Man (Elite)]]| }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[England's Strongest Man2011 |England's Strongest Man (UKSC)]]| }}\n}}\n\n'''Edward Stephen Hall''' (born 15 January 1988) is an English former professional [[strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]], notable for winning the [[World's Strongest Man]] 2017 competition<ref>{{cite news|title=Britain's Eddie Hall defeats Game of Thrones star The Mountain to be crowned World's Strongest Man|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2017/05/28/britains-eddie-hall-defeats-game-thrones-star-mountain-crowned/|newspaper=Telegraph|accessdate=28 May 2017|date=28 May 2017|last1=Sport|first1=Telegraph}}</ref> and for being the world record [[deadlift]] holder, lifting {{Convert|500|kg|lb st|0|abbr=on}} under strongman rules, which he achieved in 2016.<ref name=\"breakrecord\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/arnold-schwarzenegger-left-hanging-after-strongman-athlete-eddie-hall-breaks-deadlift-record-with-incredible-462kg-lift-10118808.html | title=Eddie Hall breaks deadlift record with incredible 462kg lift | publisher=The Independent | date=19 March 2015 | accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref> He has also won on multiple occasions both the [[UK Strength Council|UK's Strongest Man]] and [[Strength athletics in the United Kingdom and Ireland|England's Strongest Man]] titles.\n\n== Early life and beginnings ==\nHall was born on 15 January 1988 in [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], [[Staffordshire]].<ref name=bio>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/athletes/ed-hall/|title=Ed Hall|website=[[World's Strongest Man]]}}</ref> As a teenager, he was a successful competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and [[rugby union]] player. Hall attended Clayton High School, but was expelled at the age of 15. Soon afterwards, he received [[in-home tutoring]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Eddie 'The Beast' |title=Strongman: My Story |date=2017 |publisher=Ebury Publishing |isbn=9780753548721 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_DpbDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=eddie+hall#v=onepage&q=eddie%20hall&f=false |accessdate=3 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2008, he began working as a mechanic in the garage at the Robert Wiseman Dairies site in [[Market Drayton]], [[Shropshire]].<ref name=\"shrop\">[http://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2011/09/02/market-draytons-eddie-hall-is-britains-strongest-man/ Market Drayton's Eddie Hall is Britain's Strongest Man]. Shropshirestar.com (2 September 2011). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref> He trained and competed as a bodybuilder and entered the strongman circuit, having done a strongman competition at the Iceman gym in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], Staffordshire. In 2010, Dave Meer of [[Tamworth, Staffordshire]] had to drop out of the England championships organised by Elite Strongman because of injury. He arranged for Hall to take his place and led to Hall making it into the 2010 finals, which he won on his first attempt by half a point.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/stoke/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8997000/8997517.stm Eddy Hall wins England's Strongest Man 2010 contest]. BBC News (14 September 2010). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nHall finished first at the [[UK Strength Council|UK's Strongest Man]] 2011 competition in [[Belfast]], with Ken Nowicki in 2nd and Rich Smith in 3rd.<ref>[http://www.irishstrongman.com/competitions/viewdetails2.asp?ID=93 UK Strongest Man is Ed Hall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110084633/http://www.irishstrongman.com/competitions/viewdetails2.asp?ID=93 |date=10 January 2015 }}. Irishstrongman.com. Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref> His win was helped by setting a new national record in the \"Viking Hold\", hanging on to 20&nbsp;kg (44lbs) axes in each hand at full stretch for one minute and 18 seconds. Hall tore tendons in an arm during the competition, but was hopeful of a spot at the World's Strongest Man in September. However, his improved ranking could only guarantee a spot for 2012, and he did not compete at WSM in 2011.<ref>[http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Sport-Hall-conquers-UK-wants-world/story-13275267-detail/story.html Hall conquers UK ... now he wants to take on the world]. Thisisstaffordshire.co.uk (6 September 2011). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref>\n\nWinning the UK title meant that Hall became the first choice to replace Jono MacFarlane of [[New Zealand]] in the [[Giants Live]] [[Melbourne]] event in February 2012, when the latter suffered a back injury.<ref>[http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2012/Feb/Ed_Hall_Named_to_Giants_Live-Melbourne_Start_List.html Sunday, 19 February 2012 '&#39;Ed Hall Named to Giants Live\u2013Melbourne Start List'&#39; by Randall J. Strossen, Ph.D]. Ironmind.com (19 February 2012). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref> He placed fourth in his first taste of international competition. Later, in April 2012, he was invited to compete at [[Europe's Strongest Man]], another Giants Live event. This was held at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley Carnegie Stadium]], home of the [[Leeds Rhinos]] rugby league team and Hall found himself competing alongside six of the ten finalists from World's Strongest Man 2011, including four-time World's Strongest Man, [[\u017dydr\u016bnas Savickas]]. Hall finished in eighth place.<ref>[http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/2012-wsm/europes-strongest-man-results/ Europe's strongest man results 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829140448/http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/2012-wsm/europes-strongest-man-results/ |date=29 August 2012 }}. Theworldsstrongestman.com (25 June 2012). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Hall failed to qualify for Europe's Strongest Man 2013. However, he was given a second chance when [[Ervin Katona]] was forced to retire due to injury. Hall competed in his place and came in eighth place. In April, Hall also featured on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'' programme, who enlisted his help to test even the strongest of drivers in specific circumstances.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00rks8s Watchdog Series 29, Episode 7, Fiat: Steering that]. bbc.co.uk (26 April 2012). Retrieved on 11 January 2013.</ref> In 2012, Hall competed at the [[World's Strongest Man]] finals, but did not progress beyond his qualifying group.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} Hall returned in 2013, winning two events in his heat but narrowly missing out on qualifying after a poor final event.\n\nIn 2014, Hall reached the final for the first time, coming second in the Squat Lift event and ultimately finishing 6th. In March 2015, Hall achieved the world record for lifting the weight of {{convert|462|kg|lb st|abbr=on}} in the deadlift.<ref name=\"breakrecord\" /> The record was achieved at the [[Arnold Sports Festival|Arnold Classic]] in Australia, and [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was present to cheer him on. He promptly broke his own record at the World Deadlift Championships 2015, with a {{convert|463|kg|lb st|abbr=on}} deadlift.<ref>{{Citation|last=Dean Wild|title=Eddie Hall World Record Deadlift 463kg / 1020lbs - WITH NO SUIT!!|date=18 November 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C7z7lWiFtgc|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"newrecord\">{{cite web |title=Eddie Hall does new Deadlift World Record 463KG - 1020lbs |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x5-mfOXF0i0 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=3 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he also finished 4th at the World's Strongest Man, an improvement of two places on the previous year. In March 2016, he achieved a new world record long bar deadlift in the Arnold Classic Strongman, by lifting {{convert|465|kg|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn December 2015 a feature documentary about Hall, titled ''[[Eddie: Strongman]]'', was released. The film, directed by [[Matt Bell (television presenter)|Matt Bell]] and produced by Tom Swanston, follows Hall for two years of his life as he strives to become the strongest man in the world.\n\nIn July 2016, Hall set a new world record in the [[deadlift]] with a lift of {{convert|500|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Dean Wild|title=500kg (1102lbs) WORLD RECORD Deadlift Eddie Hall - Includes Full Aftermath!!|date=10 July 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U4AQlamvFzs|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> besting the world record he had previously set at {{convert|465|kg|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Citation|last=Dean Wild|title=465kg Speed Rep World Record Deadlift Eddie Hall|date=11 November 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8wpTiXj37MU|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> earlier that same day. The 500&nbsp;kg lift made Hall pass out.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/whats-on/video-strongman-eddie-hall-lifts-world-record-half-a-ton-at-leeds-arena-1-8006470|title=Strongman Eddie Hall lifts world record half a ton at Leeds Arena|publisher=Yorkshire Evening Post|first=Graham|last=Walker}}</ref> He is the winner of [[2017 World's Strongest Man]] competition and announced his intention to retire from the World's Strongest Man and return to lower-weight competitions after expressing health-related concerns.<ref name=\"Eddieretires\">{{cite web|title=Eddie Hall retires from World's Strongest Man competition after Brit claims historic victory|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/eddie-hall-worlds-strongest-man-10520711|website=Mirror|publisher=Mirror|accessdate=29 May 2017|date=28 May 2017}}</ref> In an interview, Hall stated that a genetic analysis had shown that a genetic mutation that causes [[Myostatin-related muscle hypertrophy|myostatin-related muscle hypertrophy]] contributed to his large muscle mass.<ref>{{cite web | title=I got the Hercules Gene - Myostatin Deficiency - Eddie Hall London Real | website=YouTube | date=13 November 2019 | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CwawKd2DKLA | access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Hall appeared on the [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] show ''Celebs In Solitary'', where he attempted to spend five days in solitary confinement.<ref name=\"Channel 5 CIS\">[http://www.channel5.com/show/celebs-in-solitary/ Celebs In Solitary: Meltdown - Channel 5], Retrieved on 23 October 2018</ref>\n\n== Personal record ==\nIn competition:\n*[[Deadlift]] with straps and suit \u2013 {{convert|500|kg|lb st|0|}}<ref name=\":0\" /> (world record)\n*Axle press \u2013 {{convert|216|kg|lb st|0|}} (world record)\n*Rogue Elephant Bar Deadlift with straps \u2013 {{convert|465|kg|lb st|0|}}<ref>Arnold classic 2016</ref>\n*Deadlift with straps \u2013 {{convert|463|kg|lb st|0|}}\n*[[Strongman Champions League|Log lift]] \u2013 {{convert|213|kg|lb st|0|}}\n*Crossfit Grace - 60Kg  (132lbs) for 30 reps in 50 seconds (World Record)\n\nGym lifts:\n*[[Squat (exercise)|Squat]] \u2013 {{convert|405|kg|lb st|0|}}\n*[[Bench press]] \u2013 {{convert|300|kg|lb st|0|}} (equipped)<ref>{{cite web | last=Tao | first=David | title=Strongman Eddie Hall Bench Presses 584 Pounds for 6 Reps! | website=BarBend | date=8 November 2016 | url=https://barbend.com/strongman-eddie-hall-bench-presses-584-pounds-6-reps/ | quote= Years ago, a much (much) lighter Hall bench pressed (equipped) an impressive 300kg...|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Leg press]] \u2013 {{convert|1000|kg|lb st|0|}} for 10 reps<ref>{{cite web|title=Eddie Hall demonstrates 1000kg leg press - Feel the power! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=148ek5InChQ |website=Youtube|accessdate=15 December 2016|date=10 December 2012}}</ref>\n*Silver dollar deadlift \u2013 {{convert|536|kg|lb st|0|}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-qBLAw_l2dE |title=World Record Deadlift with World's Strongest Man Eddie 'The Beast' Hall |publisher=Penguin Books UK |date=18 October 2017 |accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref> (unofficial world record)\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Transformers: The Last Knight]]'' \n| Saxon Warrior\n| (Uncredited)\n|-\n|2017\n|''Born Strong''\n|Himself\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2012-2019\n|''World's Strongest Man''\n| Himself - Competitor/Pundit\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[A League of Their Own (British game show)|A League of Their Own]]''\n| Himself\n| Series 10, Episode 3\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The_Chase_(British_game_show)#Celebrity_editions|The Chase]]''\n| Himself\n| Series 8 Episode 4 \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Celebs in solitary''\n| Himself\n| 1 series\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Eddie Eats America''\n| Himself\n| 1 series\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Strongest Man in History]]''\n| Himself\n| 1 series\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=}}\n\n==External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|5483679|name=Eddie Hall}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}