{"title_page": "Jon Wynne-Tyson", "text_new": "{{short description|British writer}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Jon Wynne-Tyson\n| image      = \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1924|7|6|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Hampshire]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2020|3|26|1924|7|6|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[West Sussex]] \n| occupation = Activist, publisher, writer}}\n\n'''Jon Wynne-Tyson''' (6 July 1924 \u2013 26 March 2020) was an English author, publisher,<ref name=Walters>[[Kerry S. Walters|Walters, Kerry S.]], Portmess, Lisa, 1999, ''Ethical Vegetarianism: From Pythagoras to Peter Singer'', SUNY Press, p. 233, {{ISBN|0-7914-4044-3}}.</ref><ref name=Hoare>Hoare, Philip, 2005-05-22, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/05/22/bowyn22.xml Manuscripts and the Master,] ''Telegraph''.</ref> [[Quakers|Quaker]], activist and [[pacifist]] who founded Centaur Press in 1954.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Handley-Taylor|first1=Geoffrey|title=International Who's who in Poetry - Volume 2|date=1958|publisher=International Biographical Centre|page=155}}</ref> He ran Centaur Press from his home in [[Sussex]] and was a distinguished independent publisher.<ref name=Hoare/><ref name=Newley>Newley, Patrick, 3005-03-04, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6771 Coward\u2019s confidante - Esme Wynne], The Stage.</ref> He authored books on [[animal rights]] and [[vegetarianism]].<ref name=\"Walters\" /> He had two children.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://quaker-animals.co.uk/qca-welcome-our-new-patron-jon-wynne-tyson/|title=QCA welcomes our new patron, Jon Wynne-Tyson|last=Ryder|first=Richard D.|date=2017-02-08|website=Quaker Concern for Animals|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Life and writings ==\nWynne-Tyson was born in [[Hampshire]], England in 1924. His mother was [[Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson]], a former child actress and writer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all-creatures.org/fol/art-wynne.html|title=The Wynne-Tyson effect - Articles from The Fellowship of Life: a Christian-based vegetarian group founded in 1973|website=www.all-creatures.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> and his father was Linden Charles Tyson, an officer in the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=\"Hoare\" /> At one time Wynne-Tyson held the title of \"[[Kingdom of Redonda|King of Redonda]]\", a literary title referencing a small island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/art/what-to-see/stephen-chambers-thekingdom-redonda-arts-biggest-in-joke/|title=Stephen Chambers and the Kingdom of Redonda: art's biggest in-joke?|last=Sooke|first=Alastair|date=2017-05-14|website=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> \n\nIn 1985, he received the Animal Rights Writing Award from the [[International Society for Animal Rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all-creatures.org/fol/interview-20110604.html|title=Jon Wynne-Tyson - Interviews from The Fellowship of Life: a Christian-based vegetarian network founded in 1973|website=www.all-creatures.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> His work ''The Extended Circle'' was endorsed by animal rights philosophers [[Tom Regan]] and [[Peter Singer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://animal-friends-croatia.org/index.en.php?id=660|title=AFC - The Extended Circle|website=animal-friends-croatia.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Wynne-Tyson published the play ''Marvellous Party'' about his mother and a visit from her close friend [[No\u00ebl Coward]]. He later adapted it into a radio play which was broadcast on the BBC world service in May 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08n400b|title=BBC Radio 4 Extra - Jon Wynne-Tyson - Marvellous Party|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> \n\nHis last book was an autobiography entitled ''Finding the Words: A Publishing Life''<ref name=\"Lister\">{{cite web|url=http://textualities.net/tag/finding-the-words/|title=Finding the Words|author=Lister, Michael|year=2005|publisher=Textualities|accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref> focused on his life in publishing. His autobiography also details the friendship between his mother and No\u00ebl Coward.<ref name=\"Newley\" />\n\nIn 2016, he became a patron of Quaker Concern for Animals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Centaur Press ===\nCentaur Press was a full-time independent publishing company until it was sold in 1998. The output from Centaur Press ranged from small stories illustrated by his first wife Joan Stanton to the substantial hardback series ''Centaur Classics'', which included such titles as Leland's five-volume ''Itinerary in England and Wales'', Tyndale's translation of the ''Pentateuch'', and Burns' ''Commonplace Book''.<ref name=\"Lister\" /> The company expanded into humane education releasing titles on topics such as vegetarianism, animal rights, and related philosophy. The firm also published works of fiction (''So Say Banana Bird''), classical literature and philosophy (''The Myths of Plato'') and poetry.\n\n===Vegetarianism===\n\nWynne-Tyson was the author of the book, ''Food for a Future: The Ecological Priority of a Humane Diet'', first published in 1975. It was republished as ''Food for a Future: The Complete Case For Vegetarianism'', in 1979. The book argues from anatomy, physiology, and pathology that humans are naturally vegetarian and provides ecological necessities for giving up eating and slaughtering animals.<ref name=\"New Scientist\">Tudge, Colin. (May 22, 1975). ''A need for new recipes''. ''[[New Scientist]]''. p. 466</ref><ref name=\"Medical History\">[https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/medical-history/article/jon-wynnetyson-foodfor-a-future-the-ecological-priority-of-a-humane-diet-london-davispoynter-1975-8vo-pp-183-350/46DCA6499F4A595D886F6FB334EEDE75 ''Jon Wynne-Tyson, Food for a future; the ecological priority of a humane diet'']. (1976). ''[[Medical History (journal)|Medical History]]'' 20 (3): 332.</ref>\n\nReviewing the book in the ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine, science writer [[Colin Tudge]] commented that the \"man-is-a-vegetarian thesis is ecological unnecessary, and biology unsound\" but vegetarians do have worthwhile things to say.<ref name=\"New Scientist\"/> The book was negatively reviewed in the ''[[Medical History (journal)|Medical History]]'' journal.<ref name=\"Medical History\"/>\n\n==Published works==\n*''Civilized Alternative: Pattern for Protest'' (Centaur Press: 1972) {{ISBN|978-0900000805}}\n*''Food for a Future: The Ecological Priority of a Humane Diet'' (HarperCollins: 1975) {{ISBN|978-0706701425}}\n*''Food for a Future: The Complete Case For Vegetarianism'' (Centaur Press: 1979) {{ISBN|978-0900000973|}}\n*''So Say Banana Bird'' (Pythian: 1984) {{ISBN|978-0946849000}}\n*''[[iarchive:extendedcircled00wynn|The Extended Circle: A Dictionary of Humane Thought]]'' (Centaur Press: 1985, 2009 revised and expanded ed.) {{ISBN|978-0900001215|}}\n*''Food for a Future: How World Hunger Could be Ended by the Twenty-first Century'' (Thorsons: 1988) {{ISBN|978-0722514405|}}\n*''Marvellous Party'' (Open Gate Press: 1989) {{ISBN|978-0714541785|}}\n*''Publishing Your Own Book'' (Centaur Press: 1989) {{ISBN|978-0900001284|}} \n*''Anything Within Reason'' (Oakroyd Press: 1994) {{ISBN|978-0951221013|}}\n*''Finding the Words: A Publishing Life'' (Michael Russell Publishing Ltd.: 2004) {{ISBN|978-0859552875}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n84-58642}}\n*[https://ivu.org/people/writers/wynne-tyson.html Famous Vegetarians - Jon Wynne-Tyson]\n\n{{Religious Society of Friends}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wynne-Tyson, Jon}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare scholars]]\n[[Category:Anti-vivisectionists]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:British autobiographers]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:British pacifists]]\n[[Category:British publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:British Quakers]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Micronational leaders]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British writer}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Jon Wynne-Tyson\n| image      = \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1924|7|6|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Hampshire]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2020|3|26|1924|7|6|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[West Sussex]] \n| occupation = Activist, publisher, writer}}\n\n'''Jon Wynne-Tyson''' (6 July 1924 \u2013 26 March 2020) was an English author, publisher,<ref name=Walters>[[Kerry S. Walters|Walters, Kerry S.]], Portmess, Lisa, 1999, ''Ethical Vegetarianism: From Pythagoras to Peter Singer'', SUNY Press, p. 233, {{ISBN|0-7914-4044-3}}.</ref><ref name=Hoare>Hoare, Philip, 2005-05-22, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/05/22/bowyn22.xml Manuscripts and the Master,] ''Telegraph''.</ref> [[Quakers|Quaker]], activist and [[pacifist]] who founded Centaur Press in 1954.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Handley-Taylor|first1=Geoffrey|title=International Who's who in Poetry - Volume 2|date=1958|publisher=International Biographical Centre|page=155}}</ref> He ran Centaur Press from his home in [[Sussex]] and was a distinguished independent publisher.<ref name=Hoare/><ref name=Newley>Newley, Patrick, 3005-03-04, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6771 Coward\u2019s confidante - Esme Wynne], The Stage.</ref> He authored books on [[animal rights]] and [[vegetarianism]].<ref name=\"Walters\" /> He had two children.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://quaker-animals.co.uk/qca-welcome-our-new-patron-jon-wynne-tyson/|title=QCA welcomes our new patron, Jon Wynne-Tyson|last=Ryder|first=Richard D.|date=2017-02-08|website=Quaker Concern for Animals|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Life and writings ==\nWynne-Tyson was born in [[Hampshire]], England in 1924. His mother was [[Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson]] a former child actress and writer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all-creatures.org/fol/art-wynne.html|title=The Wynne-Tyson effect - Articles from The Fellowship of Life: a Christian-based vegetarian group founded in 1973|website=www.all-creatures.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> and his father was Linden Charles Tyson, an officer in the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=\"Hoare\" /> At one time Wynne-Tyson held the title of \"[[Kingdom of Redonda|King of Redonda]]\", a literary title referencing a small island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/art/what-to-see/stephen-chambers-thekingdom-redonda-arts-biggest-in-joke/|title=Stephen Chambers and the Kingdom of Redonda: art's biggest in-joke?|last=Sooke|first=Alastair|date=2017-05-14|website=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> \n\nIn 1985, he received the Animal Rights Writing Award from the [[International Society for Animal Rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.all-creatures.org/fol/interview-20110604.html|title=Jon Wynne-Tyson - Interviews from The Fellowship of Life: a Christian-based vegetarian network founded in 1973|website=www.all-creatures.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> His work ''The Extended Circle'' was endorsed by animal rights philosophers [[Tom Regan]] and [[Peter Singer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://animal-friends-croatia.org/index.en.php?id=660|title=AFC - The Extended Circle|website=animal-friends-croatia.org|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Wynne-Tyson published the play ''Marvellous Party'' about his mother and a visit from her close friend [[No\u00ebl Coward]]. He later adapted it into a radio play which was broadcast on the BBC world service in May 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08n400b|title=BBC Radio 4 Extra - Jon Wynne-Tyson - Marvellous Party|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> \n\nHis last book was an autobiography entitled ''Finding the Words: A Publishing Life''<ref name=\"Lister\">{{cite web|url=http://textualities.net/tag/finding-the-words/|title=Finding the Words|author=Lister, Michael|year=2005|publisher=Textualities|accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref> focused on his life in publishing. His autobiography also details the friendship between his mother and No\u00ebl Coward.<ref name=\"Newley\" />\n\nIn 2016, he became a patron of Quaker Concern for Animals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Centaur Press ===\nCentaur Press was a full-time independent publishing company until it was sold in 1998. The output from Centaur Press ranged from small stories illustrated by his first wife Joan Stanton to the substantial hardback series ''Centaur Classics'', which included such titles as Leland's five-volume ''Itinerary in England and Wales'', Tyndale's translation of the ''Pentateuch'', and Burns' ''Commonplace Book''.<ref name=\"Lister\" /> The company expanded into humane education releasing titles on topics such as vegetarianism, animal rights, and related philosophy. The firm also published works of fiction (''So Say Banana Bird''), classical literature and philosophy (''The Myths of Plato'') and poetry.\n\n===Vegetarianism===\n\nWynne-Tyson was the author of the book, ''Food for a Future: The Ecological Priority of a Humane Diet'', first published in 1975. It was republished as ''Food for a Future: The Complete Case For Vegetarianism'', in 1979. The book argues from anatomy, physiology, and pathology that humans are naturally vegetarian and provides ecological necessities for giving up eating and slaughtering animals.<ref name=\"New Scientist\">Tudge, Colin. (May 22, 1975). ''A need for new recipes''. ''[[New Scientist]]''. p. 466</ref><ref name=\"Medical History\">[https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/medical-history/article/jon-wynnetyson-foodfor-a-future-the-ecological-priority-of-a-humane-diet-london-davispoynter-1975-8vo-pp-183-350/46DCA6499F4A595D886F6FB334EEDE75 ''Jon Wynne-Tyson, Food for a future; the ecological priority of a humane diet'']. (1976). ''[[Medical History (journal)|Medical History]]'' 20 (3): 332.</ref>\n\nReviewing the book in the ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine, science writer [[Colin Tudge]] commented that the \"man-is-a-vegetarian thesis is ecological unnecessary, and biology unsound\" but vegetarians do have worthwhile things to say.<ref name=\"New Scientist\"/> The book was negatively reviewed in the ''[[Medical History (journal)|Medical History]]'' journal.<ref name=\"Medical History\"/>\n\n==Published works==\n*''Civilized Alternative: Pattern for Protest'' (Centaur Press: 1972) {{ISBN|978-0900000805}}\n*''Food for a Future: The Ecological Priority of a Humane Diet'' (HarperCollins: 1975) {{ISBN|978-0706701425}}\n*''Food for a Future: The Complete Case For Vegetarianism'' (Centaur Press: 1979) {{ISBN|978-0900000973|}}\n*''So Say Banana Bird'' (Pythian: 1984) {{ISBN|978-0946849000}}\n*''[[iarchive:extendedcircled00wynn|The Extended Circle: A Dictionary of Humane Thought]]'' (Centaur Press: 1985, 2009 revised and expanded ed.) {{ISBN|978-0900001215|}}\n*''Food for a Future: How World Hunger Could be Ended by the Twenty-first Century'' (Thorsons: 1988) {{ISBN|978-0722514405|}}\n*''Marvellous Party'' (Open Gate Press: 1989) {{ISBN|978-0714541785|}}\n*''Publishing Your Own Book'' (Centaur Press: 1989) {{ISBN|978-0900001284|}} \n*''Anything Within Reason'' (Oakroyd Press: 1994) {{ISBN|978-0951221013|}}\n*''Finding the Words: A Publishing Life'' (Michael Russell Publishing Ltd.: 2004) {{ISBN|978-0859552875}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-n84-58642}}\n*[https://ivu.org/people/writers/wynne-tyson.html Famous Vegetarians - Jon Wynne-Tyson]\n\n{{Religious Society of Friends}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wynne-Tyson, Jon}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare scholars]]\n[[Category:Anti-vivisectionists]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:British autobiographers]]\n[[Category:British humanitarians]]\n[[Category:British pacifists]]\n[[Category:British publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:British Quakers]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Micronational leaders]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism activists]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Wynne-Tyson"}
{"title_page": "DPA-713", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name = ''N'',''N''-diethyl-2-(4-methoxyphenyl)-5,7-dimethylpyrazolo[1,5-''a'']pyrimidine-3-acetamide\n| image = DPA-713.png\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = <!--             / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL         / P       / POM / CD / Class A, B, C -->\n| legal_US = <!-- OTC                   / Rx-only  / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V -->\n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =  \n| protein_bound =  \n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = \n| CAS_number = 386297-97-8\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = PQF723MLIV\n| ATC_prefix =  \n| ATC_suffix =  \n| PubChem           = 11595759\n| DrugBank_Ref = \n| DrugBank =  \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref =\n| ChemSpiderID      = 9770519\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=21 | H=26 | N=4 | O=2\n| molecular_weight = 366.46 g/mol\n| smiles            = CCN(CC)C(=O)CC1=C2N=C(C=C(N2N=C1C3=CC=C(C=C3)OC)C)C\n| StdInChI          = 1S/C21H26N4O2/c1-6-24(7-2)19(26)13-18-20(16-8-10-17(27-5)11-9-16)23-25-15(4)12-14(3)22-21(18)25/h8-12H,6-7,13H2,1-5H3\n| StdInChIKey       = ILZWUAWCTNWSFZ-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''DPA-713''' or '''''N'',''N''-diethyl-2-(4-methoxyphenyl)-5,7-dimethylpyrazolo[1,5-''a'']pyrimidine-3-acetamide''' is a selective ligand for the [[translocator protein]] (TSPO).<ref name=\"Selleri1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Selleri S, Bruni F, Costagli C, Costanzo A, Guerrini G, Ciciani G, Costa B, Martini C | title = 2-Arylpyrazolo[1,5-a]pyrimidin-3-yl acetamides. New potent and selective peripheral benzodiazepine receptor ligands | journal = Bioorg. Med. Chem. | volume = 9 | issue = 10 | pages = 2661\u20132671 | year = 2001 | month = | pmid = | doi = 10.1016/S0968-0896(01)00192-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds_2010\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reynolds A, Hanani R, Hibbs D, Damont A, Da Pozzo E, Selleri S, Doll\u00e9 F, Martini C, Kassiou M | title = Pyrazolo[1,5-a]pyrimidine acetamides: 4-Phenyl alkyl ether derivatives as potent ligands for the 18 kDa translocator protein (TSPO) | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry Letters | volume = 20 | issue = 19 | pages = 5799\u2013802 | date = October 2010 | pmid = 20727749 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmcl.2010.07.135 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[binding affinity]] of DPA-713 for TSPO is reported as ''K''<sub>i</sub> = 4.7 \u00b1 0.2 nM.<ref name=\"Selleri1\" /><ref name=\"Reynolds_2010\" />\n\nDPA-713 has been radiolabelled with [[carbon-11]] as a potential [[radiotracer]] for imaging the TSPO using [[positron emission tomography]] (PET).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = James ML, Fulton RR, Henderson DJ, Eberl S, Meikle SR, Thomson S, Allan RD, Dolle F, Fulham MJ, Kassiou M | title = Synthesis and in vivo evaluation of a novel peripheral benzodiazepine receptor PET radioligand | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 13 | issue = 22 | pages = 6188\u201394 | date = November 2005 | pmid = 16039131 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmc.2005.06.030 }}</ref><ref name=\"Thominiaux1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Thominiaux C, Doll\u00e9 F, James ML, Bramoull\u00e9 Y, Boutin H, Besret L, Gr\u00e9goire MC, Valette H, Bottlaender M, Tavitian B, Hantraye P, Selleri S, Kassiou M | title = Improved synthesis of the peripheral benzodiazepine receptor ligand [11C]DPA-713 using [11C]methyl triflate | journal = Applied Radiation and Isotopes | volume = 64 | issue = 5 | pages = 570\u20133 | date = May 2006 | pmid =  | doi = 10.1016/j.apradiso.2005.12.003 }}</ref><ref name=\"Boutin1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Boutin H, Chauveau F, Thominiaux C, Gregoire MC, James ML, Trebossen R, Hantraye P, Dolle F, Tavitian B, Kassiou M | title = <sup>11</sup>C-DPA-713: A Novel Peripheral Benzodiazepine Receptor PET Ligand for In Vivo Imaging of Neuroinflammation | journal = J. Nucl. Med. | volume = 48 | issue = 4 | pages = 573\u2013581 | year = 2007 | month = | pmid = | doi = 10.2967/jnumed.106.036764}}</ref> Radiation dosimetry and biodistribution of [<sup>11</sup>C]DPA-713 have been assessed in healthy volunteers, indicating that [<sup>11</sup>C]DPA-713 is a suitable [[radioatracer]] for imaging the TSPO in humans.<ref name=\"Endres1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Endres CJ, Pomper MG, James M, Uzuner O, Hammoud DA, Watkins CC, Reynolds A, Hilton J, Dannals RF, Kassiou M | title = Initial evaluation of 11C-DPA-713, a novel TSPO PET ligand, in humans | journal = Journal of Nuclear Medicine | volume = 50 | issue = 8 | pages = 1276\u201382 | date = August 2009 | pmid =  19617321| pmc = 2883612 | doi = 10.2967/jnumed.109.062265 }}</ref><ref name=\"Endres2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Endres CJ, Coughlin JM, Gage KL, Watkins CC, Kassiou M, Pomper MG | title = Radiation dosimetry and biodistribution of the TSPO ligand 11C-DPA-713 in humans | journal = Journal of Nuclear Medicine | volume = 53 | issue = 2 | pages = 330\u20135 | date = February 2012 | pmid =  22241913| doi = 10.2967/jnumed.111.094565 | pmc = 3274766 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[DPA-714]]\n* [[translocator protein]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrazolopyrimidines]]\n[[Category:TSPO ligands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name = ''N'',''N''-diethyl-2-(4-methoxyphenyl)-5,7-dimethylpyrazolo[1,5-''a'']pyrimidine-3-acetamide\n| image = DPA-713.png\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B            / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = <!--             / Schedule I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII, VIII -->\n| legal_UK = <!-- GSL         / P       / POM / CD /