{"title_page": "Johan Barne", "text_new": "{{MedalTableTop|medals=\n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{SWE}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Soling World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | 1992 Cadiz | Soling }}\n{{MedalSilver | 1995 Kingston | Soling }}\n{{MedalBronze | 2000 Murcia | Soling }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Soling World Matchrace Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 1996 Cadiz | Soling }}\n{{MedalGold | 1999 Melbourne | Soling }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[505 (dinghy)#World Championships|505 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2003 Malm\u00f6 | 505 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[TP 52#World Championships|TP 52 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Palma | TP52 }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2015 Puerto Portals | TP52 }}\n{{MedalGold | 2017 Scarlino | TP52 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[52 Super Series|52 super series]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2017 | TP52 }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2018 | TP52 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Melges 24|Melges 24 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2010 Tallin | Melges 24 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[5.5 Metre World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Hank\u00f8 | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Boltenhagen | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Cura\u00e7ao | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2014 Porto Santo Stefano | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2015 Nyn\u00e4shamn | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2016 Copenhagen | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2019 Helsinki | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2020 Pittswater | 5.5m }}\n}}\n\n'''Johan Barne''' (born 4 April 1964 in [[Gothenburg]]) is a Swedish Olympic sailor in the [[Soling]] class. Barne competed in [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992]], [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996]] and [[2000 Summer Olympics]], finishing fifth in the Soling in 2000 edition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sok.se/5.b17e0a10832cc6a9a80007866.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-10-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515062354/http://www.sok.se/5.b17e0a10832cc6a9a80007866.html |archive-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{World Sailing|45213|SWEJB4}}\n\n{{Footer World Champions 5.5 Metre}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Swedish Sailor of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barne, Johan}}\n[[Category:Swedish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Sweden]]\n[[Category:5.5 Metre class sailors]]\n[[Category:World Champions in 5.5 Metre]]\n[[Category:TP52 class world champions]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Royal Gothenburg Yacht Club sailors]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{MedalTableTop|medals=\n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{SWE}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Soling World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | 1992 Cadiz | Soling }}\n{{MedalSilver | 1995 Kingston | Soling }}\n{{MedalBronze | 2000 Murcia | Soling }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Soling World Matchrace Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 1996 Cadiz | Soling }}\n{{MedalGold | 1999 Melbourne | Soling }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[505_(dinghy)#World_Championships|505 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2003 Malm\u00f6 | 505 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[TP 52#World Championships|TP 52 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Palma | TP52 }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2015 Puerto Portals | TP52 }}\n{{MedalGold | 2017 Scarlino | TP52 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[52_Super_Series|52 super series]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2017 | TP52 }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2018 | TP52 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Melges_24|Melges 24 World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2010 Tallin | Melges 24 }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[5.5 Metre World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Hank\u00f8 | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2012 Boltenhagen | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Cura\u00e7ao | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2014 Porto Santo Stefano | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2015 Nyn\u00e4shamn | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2016 Copenhagen | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2019 Helsinki | 5.5m }}\n{{MedalGold | 2020 Pittswater | 5.5m }}\n}}\n\n'''Johan Barne''' (born 4 April 1964 in [[Gothenburg]]) is a Swedish Olympic sailor in the [[Soling]] class. Barne competed in [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992]], [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996]] and [[2000 Summer Olympics]], finishing fifth in the Soling in 2000 edition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sok.se/5.b17e0a10832cc6a9a80007866.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-10-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515062354/http://www.sok.se/5.b17e0a10832cc6a9a80007866.html |archive-date=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{World Sailing | id= SWEJB4}}\n\n{{Footer World Champions 5.5 Metre}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Swedish Sailor of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barne, Johan}}\n[[Category:Swedish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Sweden]]\n[[Category:5.5 Metre class sailors]]\n[[Category:World Champions in 5.5 Metre]]\n[[Category:TP52 class world champions]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Royal Gothenburg Yacht Club sailors]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update World Sailing link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johan_Barne"}
{"title_page": "Kungumam (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1963 film by Krishnan\u2013Panju}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kungumam\n| image          = Kungumam film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]]\n| producer       = [[K. Mohan]]\n| writer         = \n| screenplay     = [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n| story          = Nihar Ranjan Gupta\n| starring       = [[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]]<br />[[S. S. Rajendran]]<br />[[C. R. Vijayakumari]]<br />[[R. Muthuraman]]\n| music          = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| cinematography = S. Maruthi Rao\n| editing        = S. Panjabi<br />R. Vittal\n| studio         = Rajamani Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Sivaji Productions]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1963|08|12|df=y|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nadigarthilagam.com/filmographyp9.htm|title=Kungumam Release|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=nadigarthilagam}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 145 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Kungumam''''' ({{trans|[[Kumkuma]]}}) is a 1963 [[Tamil language]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], directed by [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]]. The film features [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]], [[S. S. Rajendran]], [[C. R. Vijayakumari]] and [[R. Muthuraman]] in the lead roles. The film, produced by [[K. Mohan]], had musical score by [[K. V. Mahadevan]] and was released on 12 August 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spicyonion.com/movie/kungumam/|title=Kungumam|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=spicyonion}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSundaram ([[Sivaji Ganesan]]) loves Gomathi ([[C. R. Vijayakumari]]), the latter is an orphan and lives with her uncle's family. Sundaram travels to the USA for further studies. When Sundaram returns four years later, he was shocked to see that his mother Vedhavalli ([[M. V. Rajamma]]) is a widow and was told that his father Sambasivam committed suicide due to the disgrace that he was unable to pay back the loans.\n\nSundaram leaves to Bombay for an interview, where comes across the murder of broker Govindan and is shocked to see that the murderer is Punniyakodi ([[S. V. Ranga Rao]]), who is later introduced as Gomathi's father in a police investigation. Sundaram helps Punniyakodi to escape and in turn is suspected by the police instead. Police Superintendent Raja ([[S. S. Rajendran]]) is appointed to investigate the murder case. When Gomathi's uncle refuses to let her marry Sundaram, she leaves home, following Vedhavalli to Madurai. Sundaram travels back to Madras where he bumps into Susila ([[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]]) on the road. Sundaram finds Govindan's family and offers help, who initially refuses but later accepts when persuaded and explained to. While leaving Govindan's house, Sundaram learns that Punniyakodi is living as a fugitive, had changed his name as James and staying with a crook Kanthan (O. A. K. Thevar). Sundaram seeks his friend Dass's ([[R. Muthuraman]]) help in taking care of Punniyakodi for the time being, goes to Madurai and explains to Vedhavalli and Gomathi that he is a murderer and wanted by the police, but Vedhavalli refuses to accept Sundaram as her son due to the conviction.\n\nSundaram, upon reading an advertisement in the newspaper, joins as a tuition teacher in disguise as Kalamegam. There, Sundaram learns that Susila's father is Justice  Somanathan ([[S. V. Sahasranamam]]), her cousin is Inspector Raja, servants Arasan ([[Nagesh]]) and Kanniyamma ([[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]). Meanwhile, Superintendent Raja hatches a plan to move Vedhavalli and Gomathi to Dass's house so to ease the capture Sundaram if he happens to visit them, but James leaves Dass's home following Kanthan's temptation. Susila refuses Raja's advances and develops a soft corner for Kalamegam, but later learns that he is Sundaram and his deeds, but lies to Justice Somanathan that he is a good man. Susila also lets Sundaram escape when Raja finds out about this.\n\nVedhavalli, who is a staunch believer of justice, hates Sundaram for his conviction and arranges for Gomathi to marry Dhas, but Gomathi refuses. In turn, Gomathi pleads to Sundaram to marry Susila as Susila had helped them out a lot to prove Sundaram's innocence before gets shot by the police, mistaken for Sundaram. A trial takes place where Sundaram accepts all the charges against him. A twist in the story occurs when Somanathan produces Punniyakodi and Kanthan in court. Punniyakodi admits in court that he was cheated by Kanthan into shooting broker Govindan, where Kanthan earlier had told Punniyakodi that the revolver was unloaded. Lastly Punniyakodi admits that he is actually Sambasivam and was introduced as Punniyakodi to the police by Sundaram, who was only doing all these in order to save him. The judges sentences Kanthan for murder, further trials for Sambasivam and six months for Sundaram. At the end of the story, Sambasivam applies Kungumam to Vedhavalli at the request of Sundaram.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Sundaram / Tamilpulavar Kalamegam / (Kaliuga Kannagi, Leady Gateup)\n*[[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]] as Susila\n*[[S. S. Rajendran]] as Raja (Superintendent of Police)\n*[[C. R. Vijayakumari]] as Gomathi\n*[[S. V. Ranga Rao]] as Punniyakodi / James / Sambasivam (Sundaram's father)\n*[[M. V. Rajamma]] as Vedhavalli (Sundaram's mother)\n*[[S. V. Sahasranamam]] as Justice Somanathan (Susila's father)\n*[[R. Muthuraman]] as Dass (Sundaram's friend)\n*[[Nagesh]] as Arasan (Susila home's servant)\n*[[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Kanniyamma (Arasan's wife)\n* S. A. Kannan as Chinnaiya (Sundaram's uncle)\n* Radha Bai as Rajamani (Sundaram's aunt)\n* [[O. A. K. Thevar]] as Kanthan (blackmailer)\n\n== Crew ==\n*Director: [[Krishnan-Panju]]\n*Producer: [[K. Mohan]]\n*Production Company: Rajamani Pictures\n*Music: [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n*Lyrics: [[Kannadasan]]\n*Story: Nihar Ranjan Gupta\n*Screenplay: [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n*Dialogues: [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n*Cinematography: S. Maruthi Rao\n*Editing: S. Panjabi & R. Vittal\n*Art Direction: [[K. Mohan]]\n*Choreography: A. K. Chopra, Rathnakumar and Janarthanam\n*Stunt: None\n*Audiography: T. S. Rangasamy, V. C. Sekar and S. P. Ramanathan\n*Dance: None\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe music was composed by [[K. V. Mahadevan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/Kungumam-t0001662|title=Kungumam Songs|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=raaga}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No. !! Song !! Singers !! Lyrics !! Length\n|-\n| 1 || \"Chinna Siriya Vannaparavai\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[S. Janaki]] || rowspan=6|[[Kannadasan]] || 05:48\n|-\n| 2 || \"Kaalangal Thorum\" || [[P. Suseela]] || 03:35\n|-\n| 3 || \"Kungumam\" || [[Soolamangalam Sisters|Soolamangalam Rajalakshmi]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 02:50\n|-\n| 4 || \"Mayakkam Enadhu\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] || 03:46\n|-\n| 5 || \"Poonthotta Kavalkara\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 03:49\n|-\n| 6 || \"Thungadha Kannendru\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 03:59\n|-\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\nWriting for ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'', T. M. Ramachandran called it \"an utterly poor film\" and also noted, \"What amazes one is the complete absence of directorial touches of Krishnan and Panju [..] by giving the public such a crude film as ''Kunkhumam''\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=T. M. |date=24 August 1963 |title=Kunkhumam |url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12015/page/n445 |magazine=[[Sport and Pastime]] |volume=20 |page=50}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001662\n* {{IMDb title|0234061|Kungumam}}\n{{Krishnan-Panju}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kungumam}}\n[[Category:1963 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Krishnan\u2013Panju]]\n[[Category:1960s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by K. V. Mahadevan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1963 film by Krishnan\u2013Panju}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kungumam\n| image          = Kungumam film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]]\n| producer       = [[K. Mohan]]\n| writer         = \n| screenplay     = [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n| story          = Nihar Ranjan Gupta\n| starring       = [[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]]<br />[[S. S. Rajendran]]<br />[[C. R. Vijayakumari]]<br />[[R. Muthuraman]]\n| music          = [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n| cinematography = S. Maruthi Rao\n| editing        = S. Panjabi<br />R. Vittal\n| studio         = Rajamani Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Sivaji Productions]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1963|08|12|df=y|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nadigarthilagam.com/filmographyp9.htm|title=Kungumam Release|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=nadigarthilagam}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 145 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Kungumam''''' ({{trans|[[Kumkuma]]}}) is a 1963 [[Tamil language]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], directed by [[Krishnan\u2013Panju]]. The film features [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]], [[S. S. Rajendran]], [[C. R. Vijayakumari]] and [[R. Muthuraman]] in the lead roles. The film, produced by [[K. Mohan]], had musical score by [[K. V. Mahadevan]] and was released on 12 August 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spicyonion.com/movie/kungumam/|title=Kungumam|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=spicyonion}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSundaram ([[Sivaji Ganesan]]) loves Gomathi ([[C. R. Vijayakumari]]), the latter is an orphan and lives with her uncle's family. Sundaram leaves to the USA for further studies. When Sundaram comes back four years later, he was shocked to see that his mother Vedhavalli ([[M. V. Rajamma]]) is a widow and was told that his father Sambasivam committed suicide due to the disgrace that he was unable to pay back the loans.\n\nSundaram leaves to Bombay for an interview, where comes across the murder of broker Govindan and is shocked to see that the murderer is Punniyakodi ([[S. V. Ranga Rao]]), who is later introduced as Gomathi's father in a police investigation. Sundaram helps Punniyakodi to escape and in turn is suspected by the police instead. Police Superintendent Raja ([[S. S. Rajendran]]) is appointed to investigate the murder case. When Gomathi's uncle refuses to let her get married to Sundaram, she leaves home, following Vedhavalli to Madurai. Sundaram travels back to Madras where he bumps into Susila ([[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]]) on the road. Sundaram finds Govindan's family and offers help, who initially refuses but later accepts when persuaded and explained to. While leaving Govindan's house, Sundaram learns that Punniyakodi is living as a fugitive, had changed his name as James and staying with a crook Kanthan (O. A. K. Thevar). Sundaram seeks his friend Dass's ([[R. Muthuraman]]) help in taking care of Punniyakodi for the time being, goes to Madurai and explains to Vedhavalli and Gomathi that he is a murderer and wanted by the police, but Vedhavalli refuses to accept Sundaram as her son due to the conviction.\n\nSundaram, upon reading an advertisement in the newspaper, joins as a tuition teacher in disguise as Kalamegam. There, Sundaram learns that Susila's father is Justice  Somanathan ([[S. V. Sahasranamam]]), her cousin is Inspector Raja, servants Arasan ([[Nagesh]]) and Kanniyamma ([[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]]). Meanwhile, Superintendent Raja hatches a plan to move Vedhavalli and Gomathi to Dass's house so to ease the capture Sundaram if he happens to visit them, but James leaves Dass's home following Kanthan's temptation. Susila refuses Raja's advances and develops a soft corner for Kalamegam, but later finds out that he is Sundaram and his deeds, but lies to Justice Somanathan that he is a good man. Susila also lets Sundaram escape when Raja finds out about this.\n\nVedhavalli, who is a staunch believer of justice, hates Sundaram for his conviction and arranges Gomathi to be married to Dhas, but Gomathi refuses. In turn, Gomathi pleads to Sundaram to marry Susila as Susila had helped them out a lot to prove Sundaram's innocence before gets shot by the police, mistaken for Sundaram. A trial takes place where Sundaram accepts all the charges against him. A twist in the story occurs when Somanathan produces Punniyakodi and Kanthan in court. Punniyakodi admits in court that he was cheated by Kanthan into shooting broker Govindan, where Kanthan earlier had told Punniyakodi that the revolver was unloaded. Lastly Punniyakodi admits that he is actually Sambasivam and was introduced as Punniyakodi to the police by Sundaram, who was only doing all these in order to save him. The judges sentences Kanthan for murder, further trials for Sambasivam and 6 months for Sundaram. At the end of the story, Sambasivam applies kungumam to Vedhavalli at the request of Sundaram.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Sundaram / Tamilpulavar Kalamegam / (Kaliuga Kannagi, Leady Gateup)\n*[[Sharada (actress)|Saratha]] as Susila\n*[[S. S. Rajendran]] as Raja (Superintendent of Police)\n*[[C. R. Vijayakumari]] as Gomathi\n*[[S. V. Ranga Rao]] as Punniyakodi / James / Sambasivam (Sundaram Father)\n*[[M. V. Rajamma]]  as Vedhavalli (Sundaram Mother)\n*[[S. V. Sahasranamam]] as Justice Somanathan (Susila Father)\n*[[R. Muthuraman]] as Dass (Sundaram Friend)\n*[[Nagesh]] as Arasan (Susila Home, Servant)\n*[[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Kanniyamma (Arasan Wife)\n* S. A. Kannan as Chinnaiya (Sundaram Ungel)\n* Radha Bai as Rajamani (Sundaram Unty)\n* [[O. A. K. Thevar]] as Kanthan (Black Mailer, Enemy role)\n\n== Crew ==\n*Director: [[Krishnan-Panju]]\n*Producer: [[K. Mohan]]\n*Production Company: Rajamani Pictures\n*Music: [[K. V. Mahadevan]]\n*Lyrics: [[Kannadasan]]\n*Story: Nihar Ranjan Gupta\n*Screenplay: [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n*Dialogues: [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]]\n*Cinematography: S. Maruthi Rao\n*Editing: S. Panjabi & R. Vittal\n*Art Direction: [[K. Mohan]]\n*Choreography: A. K. Chopra, Rathnakumar & Janarthanam\n*Stunt: None\n*Audiography: T. S. Rangasamy, V. C. Sekar & S. P. Ramanathan\n*Dance: None\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe music was composed by [[K. V. Mahadevan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/Kungumam-t0001662|title=Kungumam Songs|accessdate=6 January 2015|publisher=raaga}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No. !! Song !! Singers !! Lyrics !! Length\n|-\n| 1 || \"Chinna Siriya Vannaparavai\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[S. Janaki]] || rowspan=6|[[Kannadasan]] || 05:48\n|-\n| 2 || \"Kaalangal Thorum\" || [[P. Suseela]] || 03:35\n|-\n| 3 || \"Kungumam\" || [[Soolamangalam Sisters|Soolamangalam Rajalakshmi]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 02:50\n|-\n| 4 || \"Mayakkam Enadhu\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] || 03:46\n|-\n| 5 || \"Poonthotta Kavalkara\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 03:49\n|-\n| 6 || \"Thungadha Kannendru\" || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] & [[P. Suseela]] || 03:59\n|-\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\nWriting for ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'', T. M. Ramachandran called it \"an utterly poor film\" and also noted, \"What amazes one is the complete absence of directorial touches of Krishnan and Panju [..] by giving the public such a crude film as ''Kunkhumam''\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=T. M. |date=24 August 1963 |title=Kunkhumam |url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.12015/page/n445 |magazine=[[Sport and Pastime]] |volume=20 |page=50}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001662\n* {{IMDb title|0234061|Kungumam}}\n{{Krishnan-Panju}